"(1) (i) The air inside the dome shimmered with a faint, electric hum, the kind that always clung to the metal skin of Mercury’s twilight station. Scarlet’s breath fogged the glass viewport as she watched the endless orange horizon of the inner planet roll beneath the observatory’s curved ceiling.\n(2) Outside, the solar wind howled, but inside, silence pressed against her ears except for the steady thrum of life support and the distant click of data streams. (ii) Her fingers drummed against the control panel, the tactile interface glowing with shifting glyphs and soft pulses of cerulean light.\n(3) The main hub pulsed with the usual symphony of telemetry feeds, each one a thread in the tapestry of the observatory’s purpose: to monitor subspace signals from across the solar system. She’d spent hours here, calibrating the primary array, but today felt different—tense, as if the universe itself was holding its breath.\n(4) (iii) A flicker in the upper status display caught her eye.\n(5) The green indicator for Subspace Array Alpha-7 stuttered, then went dark. Mercury Twilight Observatory. Scarlett Thomas.\n(6) At first, Scarlett assumed it was a transient glitch, a common occurrence during solar flares.\n(7) She reached for the diagnostic tool, her practiced hand moving with confidence, but the screen only displayed error codes she hadn’t seen in years.\n(8) (iv) The room seemed to grow colder, the ambient lights dimming to a soft amber as the system tried to compensate.\n(9) Alarms began to chirp, their tones sharp and insistent, slicing through the silence. April 09, 2226.\n(10) Scarlett’s pulse quickened, her mind racing. witnessed a subspace antenna failure."